	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p>The Chaldaic Dialect has a very close resemblance<lb/> to the Syriac&#58; hence they are both frequently referred<lb/> to under the common name of Aramean.  Its alpha&#61;<lb/>betical character &#38; mode of writing are the same with<lb/> the Hebrew.  Its conjugations are I Peal &#40;Kal. H.&#41; pass.<lb/> Ethpeel&#58; II Pael &#40;piel. H&#41; pass. Ethpaal&#58; III aphel<lb/> &#40;Highest H.&#41;</p>
				<p>The Syriac vowels are five. viz.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Pethotho <add>&#63;</add> or <add>&#63;</add> a</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Rebotso <add>&#63;</add> or <add>&#63;</add> e</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Hebotso <add>&#63;</add> i</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Zekopho <add>&#63;</add> o</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Etsotso <add>&#63;</add> or <add>&#63;</add> u</p>
				<p>The three first characters in the left hand column are<lb/> written either above or below the line.  The Syriac has<lb/> no sign for dagech nor for sheva.  The linea occultans<lb/> &#61; is placed under a letter to show that it is mute&#59; thus<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> bath &#40;not barth&#41; a daughter.  The other diacritical<lb/> sepsis are of minor importance.  The conjugations are<lb/> I Pial pass Ethpeel. II Pael&#44; pass. Ethpael&#59; III aphel.</p>
				<p>The Arabic vowels are only three&#58; viz.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Fatha <add>&#63;</add> a&#44; e.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Kesra <add>&#63;</add> e&#44; i.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dharma <add>&#63;</add> o&#44; u.    These vowels become<lb/> long when followed by a homogeneous quiescent.  When<lb/> followed by any other quiescent&#44; they form dipthongs&#59;<lb/> as <add>&#63;</add>&#39;s <hi rend="underline">lau</hi>.  The diacritical signs are</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Jesm <add>&#63;</add> or quiescent sheva</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Teshdid <add>&#63;</add> or Dagesh forte</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Hauza <add>&#63;</add> placed over Elif when radical</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Nesta <add>&#63;</add> placed over initial Elif&#44; showing<lb/> that the word if joined in pronunciation with the pre&#45;<lb/>ceding medda <add>&#63;</add> placed over Elif as a sign of<lb/> prolongation.</p>
				<p>Nunnation or double final vowels&#44; <add>&#63;</add> showing that<lb/> they are to be pronounced <hi rend="underline">au</hi>&#44; <hi rend="underline">eu</hi> or <hi rend="underline">iu</hi>&#44; on <hi rend="underline">or</hi> un.  It occurs only<lb/> in the Koran &#38; in poetry.  Conjugations are very numerous.</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>The <hi rend="underline">Persians</hi> use the arabic alphabet with the<lb/> addition of <add>&#63;</add> for <hi rend="underline">p</hi>. <add>&#63;</add> for <hi rend="underline">ch</hi> as in church&#58; <add>&#63;</add> or<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> for <hi rend="underline">g</hi> hard&#58; and <hi rend="underline"><add>&#63;</add> for zh</hi>.</p>
				<p>Chald. <persName>Dan.</persName> 2. 4 to 7. 28.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Ezra</persName> 48 to 6.18 also 7.12&#45;27&#95;S2.5 Ges. Gram.</p>
